To master Virtual Threads (Project Loom), you need to move beyond simple syntax and understand how they fundamentally change the economics of Java concurrency.
This plan is structured to take you from a "Thread-per-Request" mindset to a "Million-Threads-per-App" architecture.
Phase 1: The Mechanical Mental Model
Before writing code, you must understand the M:N scheduling model.
 * The "Carrier" Thread: This is the underlying OS/Platform thread (the "M").
 * The "Virtual" Thread: This is the lightweight JVM-managed thread (the "N").
 * Continuations: Learn how the JVM "pauses" a virtual thread’s stack and "unmounts" it from the carrier thread during I/O, then "mounts" it back when the I/O is done.
> Mastery Goal: Explain to a peer exactly why a virtual thread waiting for a database response doesn't consume any CPU or OS thread resources.
> 
Phase 2: Core API & Lifecycle Management
Stop using new Thread() and start using the builders and modern executors.
 * Thread Builders: Practice using Thread.ofVirtual().name("worker-", 0).start(runnable).
 * The New Executor: Master Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor().
 * Scoping: Learn the try-with-resources pattern with executors. In Java 21, ExecutorService implements AutoCloseable, meaning the code waits for all threads to finish before exiting the block.
Phase 3: The "Unlearning" Curve (The Hard Part)
Mastery requires breaking old habits that were necessary for heavy OS threads.
 * Stop Pooling: Virtual threads are like strings; they are cheap and disposable. You should never pool them. If you need to limit concurrency (e.g., only 50 database connections), use a Semaphore, not a fixed thread pool.
 * Eliminate Pinning: Learn to identify "Thread Pinning." This happens when a virtual thread is stuck on a carrier thread because it’s inside a synchronized block or calling a native method.
   * Action: Practice refactoring synchronized blocks into java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock.
Phase 4: Framework & Database Integration
This is where the theory meets enterprise production.
 * Spring Boot 3.2+: Enable spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true and observe how Tomcat and @Async tasks change.
 * Database Connectivity: High concurrency puts immense pressure on connection pools (like HikariCP). Learn to tune pool sizes and understand that while you have 10,000 threads, you still only have X database connections.
 * High-Volume Processing: Experiment with using virtual threads inside Spring Batch TaskExecutor implementations to see how it affects chunk processing speed.
Phase 5: Observability & Diagnostics
A thread dump with 100,000 threads is a nightmare. You need new tools.
 * JDK Flight Recorder (JFR): Learn to use JFR to find "Pinning" events (jdk.VirtualThreadPinned).
 * The New Thread Dump: Practice using jcmd <pid> Thread.dump_to_file -format=json to analyze thread states.
 * Memory Footprint: Monitor the Heap memory. While virtual threads are light, their stacks live on the Heap, not the OS stack memory.
Summary Table: Old vs. New
| Feature | Platform Threads (Old) | Virtual Threads (New) |
|---|---|---|
| Creation Cost | Expensive (approx. 1MB/thread) | Negligible (approx. 1KB/thread) |
| Limit | Thousands | Millions |
| Strategy | Thread Pooling | New Thread Per Task |
| I/O Handling | Blocks the OS Thread | Yields the OS Thread |
| Synchronization | synchronized is fine | Prefer ReentrantLock |
